{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17243"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17243"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.33,0.13,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77901"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9933"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17243"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"},{"type":"tags","id":"10774"},{"type":"tags","id":"10960"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23293"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77901"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProto-oncogenes are genes that encode proteins involved in normal cellular growth signalling pathways. When mutated, these genes can transform into cancer-causing oncogenes. Common examples include the RAS, MYC, and ABL genes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how proto-oncogenes typically contribute to cancer development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased protein production from gene mutations","Complete inactivation of gene transcription","Loss of regulatory function via deletions","Epigenetic silencing via DNA methylation","Enhanced protein activity via activating mutations"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EProto-oncogenes typically contribute to cancer development through \u003Cstrong\u003Eenhanced protein activity via activating mutations\u003C/strong\u003E. These gain-of-function mutations create constitutively active proteins or lead to protein overexpression. The activated oncoproteins then drive excessive cell proliferation, survival, and other cancer-promoting processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mechanisms of proto-oncogene activation include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPoint mutations that create constitutively active proteins (e.g. RAS mutations)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGene amplification leading to overexpression (e.g. ERBB2/HER2 in breast cancer)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EChromosomal translocations creating fusion proteins (e.g. BCR-ABL in chronic myeloid leukaemia)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent mechanisms that do not apply to proto-oncogenes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased protein production from gene mutations\u003C/strong\u003E - Proto-oncogenes become more active, not less active, in cancer\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete inactivation of gene transcription\u003C/strong\u003E - This would prevent oncogenic activity rather than promote it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of regulatory function via deletions\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes tumour suppressor genes, which protect against cancer when functional\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpigenetic silencing via DNA methylation\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA methylation typically silences tumour suppressor genes, not proto-oncogenes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis distinction between proto-oncogene activation and tumour suppressor gene inactivation is fundamental to understanding cancer genetics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Proto-oncogenes are normal genes that regulate cell growth and division but can become cancer-promoting when mutated.","Gain-of-function mutations in proto-oncogenes create oncogenes that drive excessive cell proliferation.","Common mechanisms of proto-oncogene activation include point mutations, gene amplification, and chromosomal translocations."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17243"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:27:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:29:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9933"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77901"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0